'''Daniel Muñoz Mejía''' (born 26 May 1996) is a Colombian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Full-back (association football)|right-back]] or [[right wing-back]] for {{English football updater|CrystalP}} club [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] and the [[Colombia national football team|Colombia national team]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en24.news/|title=DJTOGEL – Bandar Toto Online Terpercaya dan Game Online Terlengkap|website=djtogel}}</ref>

Muñoz began his career after being signed by [[Águilas Doradas]] aged 20, making his senior debut in 2017, before joining [[Atlético Nacional]] in 2019. The following year, he was signed by Belgian club [[K.R.C. Genk|Genk]], where he won the [[2020–21 Belgian Cup|Belgian Cup]] in [[2021 Belgian Cup final|2021]]. After making nearly 150 appearances for [[K.R.C. Genk|Genk]], Muñoz joined [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] in 2024. He played a key role in the team's success, providing the decisive assist in the 1–0 victory over [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in the [[2025 FA Cup final]], earning man of the match honours, and helping the club secure the [[2025 FA Community Shield|FA Community Shield]] later that year.

Muñoz made his debut for Colombia in 2021. He represented his country at the [[2021 Copa América|2021]] and [[2024 Copa América]], helping Colombia to a runners-up finish in the latter.

== Club career ==

=== Rionegro Águilas and Atlético Nacional (2017–2020) ===
A lifelong supporter of [[Atlético Nacional]], Muñoz was once part of the Los del Sur supporters' group; he left the terraces to focus on his playing career and soon impressed coaches with his energy and versatility.<ref name="auto2">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elcolombiano.com/deportes/de-barrista-a-la-mejor-liga-del-mundo-la-historia-de-daniel-munoz-JD23641844|title=Daniel Muñoz: la historia del hincha que se convirtió en héroe de Colombia|first=Sebastián Manco|last=Betancur|date=31 January 2024|website=El Colombiano}}</ref>

Daniel Muñoz's professional breakthrough came relatively late. After youth stints with [[Envigado Fútbol Club|Envigado]] and a failed attempt to sign with clubs abroad, he returned to Medellín and joined the amateur side Total Soccer. From there he earned a call-up to [[Águilas Doradas Rionegro|Rionegro Águilas]] (then Águilas Doradas) and made his professional debut at age 20 in early 2017.<ref name="auto2"/><ref name="auto">{{Cite web|url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/deportes/futbol/daniel-munoz-de-alentar-desde-la-tribuna-con-la-barra-de-atletico-nacional-de-medellin-a-ser-la-nid28062024/|title=Daniel Muñoz, de alentar desde la tribuna con la barra de Atlético Nacional de Medellín a ser la flecha derecha de Colombia|first=Franco|last=Tossi|date=28 June 2024|website=LA NACION}}</ref>

His performances for [[Águilas Doradas Rionegro|Águilas]] quickly drew attention, and within two seasons he secured a move to [[Atlético Nacional]].<ref name="auto"/> At Nacional, Muñoz developed into one of Colombia's most productive right-backs. In the [[2019 Categoría Primera A season#Finalización|2019 Finalización]] tournament he scored seven goals and provided two assists, the most goal involvements in the team, while also leading Nacional in tackles (48) and aerial duels won (47).<ref>https://www.dimayor.com.co/2020/12/ligabbva/11-ideal-de-la-liga-betplay-dimayor-ii-2019/ {{Dead link|date=May 2026}}{{Bare URL inline|date=May 2026}}</ref> His rapid rise saw him captain the side despite making only 33 appearances, fulfilling his childhood dream of representing Nacional and earning a call-up to the [[Colombia national football team|Colombian national team]].<ref name="auto2"/>

=== Genk (2020–2024) ===
In May 2020, Muñoz completed a transfer from [[Atlético Nacional]] to [[K.R.C. Genk|Genk]] in the [[Belgian Pro League]] for a reported fee of €4.5 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/genk-deal-on-daniel-munoz|title=GENK – Deal on Daniel MUNOZ|date=29 May 2020|website=GhanaSoccernet}}</ref> Muñoz quickly established himself as a key figure in Genk's defensive setup, noted for his versatility in playing both as a right-back and wing-back.

During his first full season, he contributed to Genk's victory in the [[Belgian Cup]] final against [[Standard Liège]] in April 2021, securing his first major European trophy.<ref>https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-belgium-genk/genk-claim-belgian-cup-with-win-over-standard-idUKKBN2C40O9 {{Dead link|date=May 2026}}{{Bare URL inline|date=May 2026}}</ref> Over subsequent seasons, Muñoz became one of the most consistent performers in the Belgian league, combining defensive solidity with attacking contributions. He regularly ranked among the top full-backs in the league for tackles won and progressive runs, while also chipping in with goals from set-pieces and late runs into the box.<ref>https://www.eltiempo.com/deportes/futbol-internacional/daniel-munoz-brilla-en-genk-en-la-liga-belgica-631944 {{Dead link|date=May 2026}}{{Bare URL inline|date=May 2026}}</ref>

Muñoz was instrumental in Genk's 2022–23 campaign, where the club finished as league runners-up after a close title race with [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Antwerp]].<ref>https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/65760084 {{Dead link|date=May 2026}}{{Bare URL inline|date=May 2026}}</ref> His performances earned him recognition in the league's seasonal Best XI and further solidified his place in the [[Colombia national football team|Colombian national team]].<ref>https://www.marca.com/claro-mx/futbol-internacional/2023/06/05/647de430e2704e2c058b45a5.html {{Dead link|date=May 2026}}{{Bare URL inline|date=May 2026}}</ref>

=== Crystal Palace (2024–present) ===

In January 2024, Muñoz joined [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] from [[K.R.C. Genk|Genk]] for a reported £6.6 million (€8 million), signing a contract until 2027.<ref>{{Cite news |last=McVeigh |first=Niall |last2=Davies |first2=Tom |last3=McVeigh (now) |first3=Niall |last4=Davies (earlier |first4=Tom |date=2024-01-30 |title=January transfers: Palace sign Muñoz, Villa agree Rogers fee – as it happened |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2024/jan/30/january-transfer-window-news-done-deals-premier-league-live |access-date=2026-05-29 |work=the Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cpfc.co.uk/news/announcement/daniel-munoz-signs-crystal-palace/|title=Crystal Palace sign Daniel Muñoz – News|date=30 January 2024|website=Crystal Palace F.C.}}</ref>

==== 2023–24 (half season) ====
Muñoz made his debut for Palace on 3 February 2024 in a 4–1 defeat to [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68115067|title=Brighton & Hove Albion 4–1 Crystal Palace: Seagulls beat rivals to put pressure on Roy Hodgson|date=2 February 2024|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref> He went on to make 16 league appearances during the remainder of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Daniel Muñoz Crystal Palace Defender, Profile & Stats |url=https://www.premierleague.com/en/players/247348/Daniel-Mu%C3%B1oz/overview |access-date=29 May 2026 |website=[[Premier League]]}}</ref>

==== 2024–25 season ====
Operating under manager [[Oliver Glasner]], Muñoz became a fixture in Palace's starting XI. On 5 April 2025, he scored the winning goal in a 2–1 victory over [[Brighton & Hove Albion|Brighton]] at Selhurst Park.<ref>https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/soccer-munoz-strike-gives-nine-man-palace-2-1-win-over-brighton-2025-04-05/ {{Dead link|date=May 2026}}{{Bare URL inline|date=May 2026}}</ref>

On 17 May 2025, in the [[2025 FA Cup final]] at [[Wembley Stadium]], Muñoz delivered the assist from the right flank that [[Eberechi Eze]] volleyed home for the winning goal in a 1–0 victory over [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]].<ref name="auto3">https://www.reuters.com/sports/football/palace-stun-man-city-1-0-win-first-fa-cup-2025-05-17/ {{Dead link|date=May 2026}}{{Bare URL inline|date=May 2026}}</ref><ref name="auto1">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/may/17/crystal-palace-manchester-city-fa-cup-final-match-report|title=Crystal Palace stun Manchester City to win FA Cup amid drama and Henderson controversy|first=David|last=Hytner|date=17 May 2025|via=The Guardian}}</ref> He was subsequently named Man of the Match for his role in that final.<ref name="auto1"/><ref name="auto3"/> The win secured Palace's first-ever major trophy.<ref name="auto3"/>

In April 2025, the club confirmed that Muñoz had signed a contract extension through 2028, acknowledging his six goals, ten assists in 54 appearances across all competitions, and a cumulative 106 tackles (the highest among Premier League defenders for that season).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cpfc.co.uk/news/announcement/daniel-munoz-signs-new-crystal-palace-contract/|title=Daniel Muñoz pens new Palace deal – News|date=18 April 2025|website=Crystal Palace F.C.}}</ref>

==== 2025–26 season ====
In October 2025, in the [[UEFA Conference League]] encounter against [[Dynamo Kyiv]], Muñoz scored the first goal in a 2–0 win, thus making him the first Crystal Palace player ever to score in the main round of a European competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/bulletin/sport/crystal-palace-score-conference-league-win-b2838340.html|title=Crystal Palace set new club record with Conference League win|date=2 October 2025|website=The Independent}}</ref> On 22 November, Muñoz scored again in a 2–0 league win at [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/13472330/wolves-0-2-crystal-palace-daniel-munoz-and-yeremy-pino-goals-send-palace-fourth-as-wolves-remain-winless|title=Wolves 0–2 Crystal Palace: Daniel Munoz and Yeremy Pino goals send Palace fourth as Wolves remain winless|website=Sky Sports}}</ref>

In December 2025, Muñoz was ruled out of Crystal Palace's league and European matches due to a knee injury. Manager Oliver Glasner confirmed that the injury, sustained in training, prevented him from participating in the fixtures against [[Fulham F.C.]] on 7 December and subsequent matches later that month.<ref>https://www.foxsports.com/articles/soccer/thats-why-he-cant-play-oliver-glasner-confirms-reason-for-daniel-munoz-absence-as-crystal-palace-face-fulham-without-impressive-right {{Dead link|date=May 2026}}{{Bare URL inline|date=May 2026}}</ref>

In early 2026, Gradient Sports, an Advanced Stats site, named Muñoz the Most Athletic player in the Premier League.  Gradient defined Athletic as "a combination of speed, endurance and acceleration ability."<ref>{{Cite web |author=Ryan O'Hanlon |date=2026-02-13 |title=The Premier League's best and worst players at different skills |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/47902841/premier-league-best-worst-players-fastest-slowest-passer-dribbler-superlatives |access-date=2026-02-24 |website=ESPN |language=en}}</ref>

==International career==
Muñoz was called up to the [[Colombia national football team|Colombia national team]] in September 2019, but had to withdraw with a hamstring injury.<ref>{{cite web |title=Defender Munoz cut from Colombia squad for friendlies – Xinhua {{!}} English.news.cn |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-09/01/c_138355286.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240629110612/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-09/01/c_138355286.htm |archive-date=29 June 2024 |website=xinhuanet.com |access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref> In March 2020, he was again called up by [[Carlos Queiroz]] to the national team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://es.onefootball.com/%E2%9A%A1daniel-munoz-fue-llamado-a-la-seleccion-de-colombia/|title=Daniel Muñoz fue llamado a la Selección de Colombia|language=es|website=onefootball.com|publisher=One Football|date=9 March 2020|access-date=1 April 2021}}</ref>

He made his debut on 3 June 2021 in a [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|World Cup qualifier]] against Peru. He substituted [[Stefan Medina]] in the 56th minute. In less than a minute he committed a foul which was upgraded to a [[Red card (association football)|red card]] after a [[Video assistant referee|VAR review]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[ESPN]]|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/commentary?gameId=561065|title=Peru v Colombia game report|date=3 June 2021}}</ref>

Muñoz scored his first international goal on 22 March 2024, on an assist from [[Luis Díaz (footballer, born 1997)|Luis Díaz]] in a 1–0 win against [[Spain national football team|Spain]] in a friendly match, Colombia's first ever victory against the Spaniards.<ref name ="ColombiavSpain">{{cite web|publisher=[[ESPN Colombia]]|url=https://www.espn.com.co/futbol/partido/_/juegoId/698122/colombia-espana|title=España 0, Colombia 1|date=24 March 2024}}</ref>

On 14 June 2024, Muñoz was named into 26-man [[Colombia national football team|squad]] for [[2024 Copa América]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=14 June 2024 |title=Convocatoria de la Selección Masculina de Mayores para la CONMEBOL Copa América USA 2024 |url=https://www.fcf.com.co/2024/06/14/convocatoria-de-la-seleccion-masculina-de-mayores-para-la-conmebol-copa-america-usa-2024/ |access-date=2024-10-20 |website=Federación Colombiana de Futbol |language=es}}</ref> During the competition, Muñoz played six of seven matches as a starter, scoring two goals, the first one against [[Paraguay national football team|Paraguay]] in first group phase game, scoring the first goal for a 2–1 win;<ref>{{Cite web |date=24 June 2024 |title=Colombia 2–1 Paraguay (24 de Jun., 2024) Resultado Final – ESPN (CO) |url=https://www.espn.com.co/futbol/partido/_/juegoId/690711/paraguay-colombia |access-date=2024-10-20 |website=ESPN |language=es}}</ref> and the second one against [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] into third group phase game, drawing the match 1–1 for Colombia.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2 July 2024 |title=Brasil 1–1 Colombia (2 de Jul., 2024) Resultado Final – ESPN (CO) |url=https://www.espn.com.co/futbol/partido/_/juegoId/690728/colombia-brasil |access-date=2024-10-20 |website=ESPN |language=es}}</ref> He played all matches except the final because of his expulsion after receiving a second yellow card in the semifinals against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]],<ref>{{Cite web |date=10 July 2024 |title=Colombia 1–0 Uruguay (10 de Jul., 2024) Resultado Final – ESPN (CO) |url=https://www.espn.com.co/futbol/partido/_/juegoId/703951/colombia-uruguay |access-date=2024-10-20 |website=ESPN |language=es}}</ref> being replaced with [[Santiago Arias]] for the [[2024 Copa América final|final]] against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]].

